  "footnotes": [
    "Lower Egypt: Nile Delta and Mediterranean coast — Memphis (Old/Middle Kingdom capital), Tanis (21st Dynasty), Alexandria (Ptolemaic/Roman capital), Cairo (Fatimid foundation, 969 CE); the Delta was always more exposed to foreign invasion and trade",
    "Upper Egypt: Nile Valley from Cairo to Aswan — Thebes/Luxor was the religious and often political capital of the New Kingdom; the Valley of the Kings is here; generally more conservative and 'Egyptian' than the cosmopolitan Delta",
    "Third Intermediate Period bifurcation: the 21st Dynasty maintained royal authority at Tanis while the High Priests of Amun effectively ruled Thebes as a theocratic state — a formal division of civil and religious power along geographic lines",
    "25th Dynasty (Kushite): the Nubian kings of Kush (modern Sudan) conquered Egypt and ruled as pharaohs; Taharqa is the most famous; they were eventually expelled by Assyria (671–656 BCE)",
    "Fatimid Cairo (969 CE): the Ismaili Shia Fatimids founded al-Qahira ('The Victorious') as their new capital; al-Azhar mosque and university were established then, making Cairo the intellectual center of the Islamic world",
    "Ali Bey al-Kabir (1769–73): Mamluk strongman who briefly declared Egyptian independence from the Ottomans and even occupied Syria; assassinated by a rival, the experiment collapsed",
    "Muhammad Ali (1805–48): Albanian Ottoman commander who seized power after Napoleon's withdrawal; modernized Egypt along European lines; his dynasty (Khedives → Kings) ruled until 1952 revolution"
  ]
